If you made it this far (first of all tysm you didn't need to), I just wanted to ask... Is this normal?

Yeah ofc everyone's experience is valid, I know that. But I can also acknowledge my position as a cis(?) white guy and ultimately that's the root of my anxiety rn. (8/?)

Like at the end of the day I'd probably be perfectly fine still identifying as a cis gay guy for the rest of my life, but I've also lived through what being closeted is like and I don't want to risk going through it again so I'd rather explore things like this more now. (7/?)

I've thought that maybe everything I'm feeling has more to do with identifying the same way as so many disgusting awful cis men out there, but there are also a lot of disgusting cis women and gender-NC people that it literally should not make a difference? (6/?)

It's just weird that I had no problem growing up with identifying as a "boy" or in relationships being referred to as my partner's "boyfriend," but the second in my adult life that needle started pointing more towards "man," I've just got this really weird feeling about it. (5/?)

To add to the confusion, I have zero issues with using he/him pronouns AT all. Would I LIKE to use they/them now and then? Maybe..? But it just feels silly and like I'm pulling unnecessary attention to myself since I don't mind using he/him as it is. (4/?)

And SINCE I can't tell if it's a serious thing, I don't feel comfortably up and changing my gender identity (even though gender is literally neither here nor there) because I've been so scared to be seen as a "trender" or whatever. (3/?)

Like... I've (comfortably) identified as a cis gay guy for the last 8 years of my life but lately I've started feeling genuine discomfort when being referred to as "a man."

My anxious ass keeps downplaying it tho and I can't tell if it's actually really that bad. (2/?)
